Here is a simple C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:
```
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <cctype> // for tolower()

using namespace std;

int main() {
    string filename; // name of the file
    string word; // the word to search for
    int count = 0; // count of occurrences

    // ask for the filename and word
    cout << "Enter the filename: ";
    cin >> filename;
    cout << "Enter the word to search for: ";
    cin >> word;

    // convert the word to lower case for case insensitive search
    for (char& c : word) {
        c = tolower(c);
    }

    // open the file
    ifstream file(filename);
    if (!file) {
        cerr << "Error opening file: " << filename << endl;
        return 1;
    }

    // read the file line by line
    string line;
    while (getline(file, line)) {
        // convert the line to lower case for case insensitive search
        for (char& c : line) {
            c = tolower(c);
        }

        // count the occurrences of the word
        size_t pos = line.find(word);
        while (pos != string::npos) {
            count++;
            pos = line.find(word, pos + 1);
        }
    }

    // print the result
    cout << "The word '" << word << "' occurs " << count << " times in the file " << filename << "." << endl;

    return 0;
}
```
Here's how the program works:

1. It asks the user for the filename and the word to search for.
2. It converts the word to lower case for case insensitive search.
3. It opens the file and reads it line by line.
4. For each line, it converts the line to lower case for case insensitive search.
5. It uses the `find` method to search for the word in the line, and increments a counter each time it finds the word.
6. It prints the result: the number of occurrences of the word in the file.

Note that this program assumes that the word is a single word (i.e., it doesn't contain spaces). If you want to search for multiple words, you'll need to modify the program accordingly. Also, this program is case insensitive, meaning that it will match words regardless of their case (e.g., "hello" and "HELLO" will be considered the same word).

Here is an example of a program in C that finds the common elements in two arrays without using any extra data structures:
```
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int arr1[] = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
    int arr2[] = {4, 5, 6, 7, 8};

    int i, j, found = 0;

    printf("Common elements in the two arrays are: ");

    for (i = 0; i < sizeof(arr1) / sizeof(arr1[0]); i++) {
        for (j = 0; j < sizeof(arr2) / sizeof(arr2[0]); j++) {
            if (arr1[i] == arr2[j]) {
                printf("%d ", arr1[i]);
                found = 1;
            }
        }
    }

    if (!found) {
        printf("No common elements found.");
    }

    return 0;
}
```
This program uses two nested loops to iterate through the two arrays. For each element in the first array, it checks if the same element exists in the second array. If it does, it prints the element and sets a flag to indicate that a common element was found. At the end of the program, it checks if any common elements were found and prints a message accordingly.

Note that this program assumes that the arrays are not empty and that the elements are of type `int`. You would need to modify the program if the arrays can be empty or if the elements are of a different type.

Also, this program has a time complexity of O(n^2) because it uses two nested loops to iterate through the arrays. This can be improved by using a more efficient algorithm, such as sorting the arrays and then using a single loop to find the common elements.
